# Trivy vulnerability ignore file
# Format: one CVE-ID or GHSA-ID per line, optionally followed by an expiry date
# Example:
#   CVE-2023-12345
#   GHSA-xxxx-yyyy-zzzz until:2026-06-01
#
# All entries below are for CVEs that are UNFIXED in Debian 13 Trixie
# (python:3.13-slim base image) with no fix available via apt-get upgrade.
# They are accepted risks, reviewed 2026-04-13. Expiry 2027-07-01 forces
# re-evaluation; remove each entry once Debian ships a patched package.

# ncurses 6.5+20250216-2: stack-based buffer overflow in infocmp
# analyze_string. HIGH. Affects libncursesw6, libtinfo6, ncurses-base,
# ncurses-bin.
CVE-2025-69720 until:2027-07-01

# systemd 257.9-1~deb13u1: arbitrary code execution or DoS via spurious
# IPC messages. HIGH. Affects libsystemd0, libudev1.
CVE-2026-29111 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: DoS via iconv() with specific character sets. MEDIUM.
# Affects libc-bin, libc6.
CVE-2026-4046 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: incorrect DNS response parsing. MEDIUM.
# Affects libc-bin, libc6.
CVE-2026-4437 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: invalid DNS hostname via gethostbyaddr. MEDIUM.
# Affects libc-bin, libc6.
CVE-2026-4438 until:2027-07-01

# systemd 257.9-1~deb13u1: privilege escalation via improper access
# control. MEDIUM. Affects libsystemd0, libudev1.
CVE-2026-4105 until:2027-07-01

# util-linux 2.41-5: TOCTOU in mount when setting up loop devices. MEDIUM.
# Affects bsdutils, libblkid1, liblastlog2-2, libmount1, libsmartcols1,
# libuuid1, login, mount, util-linux.
CVE-2026-27456 until:2027-07-01

# zlib1g 1:1.3.dfsg+really1.3.1-1+b1: DoS via infinite loop in CRC32
# combine functions. MEDIUM. Affects zlib1g.
CVE-2026-27171 until:2027-07-01

# liblzma5 (xz-utils) 5.6.4-1: DoS via buffer overflow in index decoding.
# MEDIUM. Affects liblzma5.
CVE-2026-34743 until:2027-07-01

# libcap2 1:2.73-4: privilege escalation via TOCTOU race in cap_setuid.
# MEDIUM. Affects libcap2.
CVE-2026-4878 until:2027-07-01

# tar 1.35+dfsg-3: hidden file injection via crafted archives. MEDIUM.
# Affects tar.
CVE-2026-5704 until:2027-07-01

# systemd 257.9-1~deb13u1: nspawn escape-to-host action via crafted optional
# config file. HIGH. Affects libsystemd0, libudev1 in python:3.13-slim.
# The application does not use systemd-nspawn; accepted risk.
CVE-2026-40226 until:2027-07-01

# systemd 257.9-1~deb13u1: udev privilege escalation via malicious hardware
# devices and unsanitized kernel output. MEDIUM. Affects libudev1.
# Attack vector requires physical access to attach a crafted hardware device
# to the host. The application is a containerised web backend deployed on
# cloud VMs (Hetzner/Fly.io); it does not use udev, does not open device
# nodes, and has no hardware enumeration code. Physical device access to
# cloud infrastructure is outside the threat model. No fix in Debian 13.
CVE-2026-40225 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: information disclosure or denial of service via ungetwc()
# with specific wide-character encodings. Affects libc-bin, libc6.
# Reachability analysis (2026-04-27):
#   - ungetwc() is a C-level wide-character stream API (push back a
#     wide character onto a FILE*).  Python 3 does NOT use ungetwc():
#     CPython's text I/O goes through its own codec layer
#     (Lib/_pyio.py + the io module), wrapping the underlying byte
#     stream — wide-character C functions are bypassed entirely.
#   - The only other glibc consumer in the image is Stockfish, which
#     speaks UCI text protocol over stdin/stdout: ASCII bytes only,
#     no wide-character I/O.  See llm/seca/engines/stockfish/pool.py
#     for how we feed it (the flat ``engine_pool.py`` referenced here
#     historically was retired in the engine-library cleanup).
#   - The exploit precondition (attacker-controlled wide-character
#     stream reaching ungetwc) does not occur in this image's
#     execution paths.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian glibc patch; remove this entry when
# `apt-get upgrade -y` ships a fixed libc6.
CVE-2026-5928 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: heap buffer overflow in scanf() with `%mc` format
# specifier and large width.  Affects libc-bin, libc6.  Confirmed via
# `trivy image` against the published API image on 2026-04-27 — same
# Trivy DB as CI, both libc-bin and libc6 entries returned no
# FixedVersion (unfixed in Debian 13 Trixie).
# Reachability analysis (2026-04-27):
#   - The vulnerable code path is the C-level scanf family with the
#     `%mc` (allocate-buffer-for-multibyte-char) modifier.  Neither
#     CPython nor any of our Python deps call scanf with %mc on
#     attacker-controlled input — Python parsing happens at the
#     interpreter level (PyArg_Parse*, struct module, etc.) and never
#     invokes scanf on byte streams from HTTP requests.
#   - Stockfish parses UCI commands with its own ad-hoc tokeniser
#     (Search/UCI.cpp), not scanf.
#   - The width-modifier overflow requires the application to pass an
#     attacker-controlled width specifier to scanf — no such code path
#     exists in this codebase.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian glibc patch; remove this entry when
# `apt-get upgrade -y` ships a fixed libc6.
CVE-2026-5450 until:2027-07-01

# util-linux 2.41-5: PAM access-control bypass via improper hostname
# canonicalization in login(1) -h <hostname>.  MEDIUM.  Affects
# bsdutils, libblkid1, liblastlog2-2, libmount1, libsmartcols1,
# libuuid1, login, mount, util-linux (9 sub-packages — all share
# the util-linux source).
# Reachability analysis (2026-05-13):
#   - The vulnerable code path is ``login(1)`` invoked with the ``-h
#     <remote_hostname>`` flag, which sets ``PAM_RHOST`` for host-based
#     PAM rules.  Exploitation requires (a) the ``login`` binary to be
#     invoked with attacker-controlled ``-h`` AND (b) PAM rules in
#     ``/etc/pam.d/*`` that key access decisions on the unsanitised
#     ``PAM_RHOST`` value.
#   - The container runs ``uvicorn llm.server:app`` as ``USER appuser``
#     (uid 10001) and never spawns ``login``.  The base image has no
#     telnetd, sshd, getty, or any other service that would invoke
#     ``login -h`` on incoming connections — only the FastAPI app
#     listens on :8000.
#   - The Dockerfile installs no ``/etc/pam.d/`` host-based rules; the
#     stock ``python:3.13-slim`` PAM config is unused at runtime
#     because no PAM-aware service is invoked.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian util-linux patch; remove this entry
# when ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed package (Debian security
# tracker shows no fix as of 2026-05-13).
CVE-2026-3184 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: out-of-bounds write in ns_printrrf / ns_printrr /
# fp_nquery when printing DNS TSIG records.  MEDIUM.  Affects libc-bin
# and libc6.
# Reachability analysis (2026-05-13):
#   - The vulnerable functions are *deprecated* DNS resource-record
#     pretty-printers (``ns_printrrf``, ``ns_printrr``, ``fp_nquery``)
#     that format TSIG records for human-readable output.  Their
#     callers are DNS administration tools like ``dig`` / ``nslookup``
#     / ``host`` and DNS server software (BIND).
#   - The container runs Python (CPython resolver uses
#     ``getaddrinfo``/``gethostbyname`` — never the ``ns_print*``
#     family) and Stockfish (no networking).  Neither imports
#     ``libresolv.so.2``'s deprecated printers.
#   - The exploit precondition requires the application to call these
#     functions on attacker-controlled DNS responses — only DNS-server
#     and DNS-debugger code paths do this, and the container ships
#     neither (slim image; no ``dig``, ``nslookup``, ``bind``, etc.).
# Accepted risk pending a Debian glibc patch; remove this entry when
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed libc6.
CVE-2026-5435 until:2027-07-01

# glibc 2.41-12: information disclosure / DoS in ns_printrrf /
# ns_printrr / fp_nquery — RDATA-length is not validated against
# RDATA content when formatting a DNS response, so a crafted RDATA
# field can cause a crash or read uninitialised memory.  MEDIUM.
# Affects libc-bin and libc6.  Same affected-function cluster as
# CVE-2026-5435 above (different upstream advisory, same call sites);
# the reachability analysis is identical and reproduced here so each
# CVE entry stands on its own without cross-reference churn:
# Reachability analysis (2026-05-27):
#   - The vulnerable functions are *deprecated* DNS resource-record
#     pretty-printers (``ns_printrrf``, ``ns_printrr``, ``fp_nquery``)
#     marked deprecated since glibc 2.34 — kept in libresolv only for
#     backwards compatibility with DNS administration tools and DNS
#     server software (dig, nslookup, host, BIND).  Per the Debian
#     security tracker, the functions "are for application debugging
#     only and hence not in the path of code executed by the DNS
#     resolver".
#   - The container runs Python (CPython resolver uses
#     ``getaddrinfo``/``gethostbyname`` — never the ``ns_print*``
#     family) and Stockfish (no networking).  Neither imports
#     ``libresolv.so.2``'s deprecated printers.
#   - The exploit precondition requires the application to call these
#     functions on attacker-controlled DNS responses — only DNS-server
#     and DNS-debugger code paths do this, and the container ships
#     neither (slim image; no ``dig``, ``nslookup``, ``bind``, etc.).
# Accepted risk pending a Debian glibc patch; remove this entry when
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed libc6 (Debian security tracker
# shows no fix as of 2026-05-27; libc6/libc-bin still 2.41-12+deb13u3).
CVE-2026-6238 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# perl-base 5.40.1-6 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): an 8-CVE cluster,
# ALL UNFIXED in Debian (no FixedVersion via ``apt-get upgrade -y``; the
# Dockerfile already runs ``apt-get upgrade -y``).  Confirmed by the Trivy
# SARIF scan on 2026-06-17 as GitHub code-scanning alerts #355-#362.
#
# ``perl-base`` is a Debian ``Essential: yes`` / ``Priority: required``
# package: it ships in every Debian base image to support dpkg/apt maintainer
# scripts and cannot be removed without breaking the package manager.  It is
# NOT an application dependency.
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-06-17) — shared by all 8 entries below:
#   - The runtime image launches ``uvicorn llm.server:app`` as USER appuser
#     (uid 10001).  The app is pure CPython; the HEALTHCHECK is python; the
#     ONLY external binary the code spawns is Stockfish, located via
#     ``shutil.which("stockfish")`` (llm/server.py:275) and driven over the
#     UCI text protocol (ASCII bytes only — see
#     llm/seca/engines/stockfish/pool.py).
#   - The perl INTERPRETER is never executed: no ``system("perl")``, no
#     subprocess spawning perl, no CGI, no ``.pl``/``.cgi`` handlers, and no
#     first-party reference to perl anywhere in ``llm/`` (grep is clean).
#   - Every vulnerable code path requires perl to run on attacker-influenced
#     input: regex/pattern compilation (CVE-2026-8376) and the Archive::Tar /
#     IO::Compress / IO::Uncompress / HTTP::Tiny modules (the other seven).
#     Those modules are not part of the minimal perl-base, and nothing in the
#     image invokes them.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian perl patch; remove each entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed perl-base.

# CVE-2026-8376 CRITICAL: heap buffer overflow compiling a crafted pattern (alert #356)
CVE-2026-8376 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-42496 CRITICAL: Archive::Tar path traversal via crafted symlinks (alert #355)
CVE-2026-42496 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-42497 HIGH: Archive::Tar extracts hardlinks to attacker paths (alert #357)
CVE-2026-42497 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-48959 HIGH: IO::Uncompress::Unzip CPU exhaustion (alert #358)
CVE-2026-48959 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-48962 HIGH: IO::Compress arbitrary code execution via output glob (alert #359)
CVE-2026-48962 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-9538 HIGH: Archive::Tar memory exhaustion (alert #360)
CVE-2026-9538 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2025-15649 MEDIUM: IO::Uncompress::Unzip propagates uncaught error (alert #361)
CVE-2025-15649 until:2027-07-01
# CVE-2026-7010 MEDIUM: HTTP::Tiny does not validate CRLF in request fields (alert #362)
CVE-2026-7010 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# libsqlite3-0 3.46.1-7+deb13u1 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): two
# FTS5 full-text-search memory-corruption CVEs, BOTH UNFIXED in Debian (no
# FixedVersion via ``apt-get upgrade -y``).  Surfaced by the Trivy SARIF scan
# on 2026-06-17 as GitHub code-scanning alerts #353 (CVE-2026-11822, HIGH —
# OOB read in fts5LeafSeek + heap write) and #354 (CVE-2026-11824, HIGH —
# heap buffer overflow in fts5ChunkIterate).
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-06-17) — shared by both entries below:
#   - Both CVEs require executing an FTS5 ``MATCH`` query against an
#     ATTACKER-CONTROLLED SQLite database (crafted FTS5 leaf / continuation
#     pages).  Exploitation is impossible without opening a malicious .sqlite
#     file AND running a full-text-search query against it.
#   - Production uses PostgreSQL (psycopg2 → Hetzner Postgres), not SQLite.
#     SQLite appears only on the dev/test path via SQLAlchemy over an
#     app-created schema; the service never opens an externally-supplied
#     database file.
#   - The codebase uses NO FTS5 extension and issues NO ``MATCH`` queries:
#     ``grep -rin "fts5\|MATCH\|enable_load_extension" llm/`` returns only
#     Python ``re.match`` hits.  The vulnerable FTS5 code path is never
#     exercised on any input this service handles.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian sqlite3 patch; remove both entries once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed libsqlite3-0.
CVE-2026-11822 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-11824 until:2027-07-01

# libbz2-1.0 1.0.8-6 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): off-by-one
# out-of-bounds write in the ``bzip2recover`` UTILITY → memory corruption /
# crash (DoS).  MEDIUM.  UNFIXED in Debian (no FixedVersion).  Surfaced by
# the Trivy SARIF scan on 2026-06-17 as GitHub code-scanning alert #352
# (CVE-2026-42250).
# Reachability analysis (2026-06-17):
#   - The flaw lives in the standalone ``bzip2recover`` command-line tool,
#     which reconstructs damaged ``.bz2`` archives.  The runtime image never
#     invokes it: no subprocess spawns ``bzip2recover``, there is no .bz2
#     recovery path, and the service processes no ``.bz2`` archives at all
#     (``grep -rin "bz2\|bzip2recover" llm/`` is clean).
#   - Python's stdlib ``bz2`` module exposes the libbz2 compression /
#     decompression routines, NOT the separate ``bzip2recover`` program where
#     this bug lives; even a bz2-using app would not reach the vulnerable
#     code.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian bzip2 patch; remove this entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed libbz2-1.0.
CVE-2026-42250 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# util-linux / libblkid 2.41-5 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): two
# partition-table PROBING memory-safety CVEs, BOTH UNFIXED in Debian (no
# FixedVersion via ``apt-get upgrade -y``; the Dockerfile already runs it).
# Surfaced by the Trivy SARIF scan on 2026-07-14 as GitHub code-scanning
# alerts #397 (CVE-2026-53615, HIGH — integer overflow in
# libblkid/src/partitions/dos.c, the MBR/DOS partition-table parser) and
# #398 (CVE-2026-13595, MEDIUM — heap use-after-free in libblkid
# nested-partition probing).  Both are in the util-linux source and Trivy
# reports them against its 9 sub-packages (bsdutils, libblkid1,
# liblastlog2-2, libmount1, libsmartcols1, libuuid1, login, mount,
# util-linux).
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-07-15) — shared by both entries below:
#   - Both flaws live in libblkid's PARTITION-TABLE probing path (dos.c and
#     the nested-partition walker).  Reaching them requires libblkid to
#     probe a block device or disk-image file carrying an attacker-crafted
#     MBR/DOS partition table — i.e. a ``blkid`` / ``mount`` / ``wipefs`` /
#     ``findfs`` invocation, or a direct ``blkid_do_probe`` call, against
#     untrusted device/image bytes.
#   - The runtime image launches ``uvicorn llm.server:app`` as USER appuser
#     (uid 10001, non-root — it cannot mount a filesystem anyway).  The ONLY
#     external binary the code spawns is Stockfish (located via
#     ``shutil.which("stockfish")`` in llm/server.py and driven over the UCI
#     text protocol — see llm/seca/engines/stockfish/pool.py).  Nothing
#     spawns blkid / mount / wipefs / findfs, and there is no first-party
#     reference to libblkid, partition tables, loop devices, or disk images
#     anywhere in ``llm/`` (``grep -rin "blkid\|losetup\|partition\|/dev/" llm/``
#     over application code returns only Python ``str.partition(" ")`` in the
#     auth-header parser).
#   - The service is a containerised web backend on cloud VMs
#     (Hetzner/Fly.io): it handles HTTP JSON, PGN/FEN text, and Postgres
#     rows — never block devices, disk images, or filesystem superblocks.
#     The vulnerable partition-probing code path is never exercised on any
#     input this service handles.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian util-linux patch; remove each entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed package (Debian security tracker
# shows no fix as of 2026-07-15).
CVE-2026-53615 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-13595 until:2027-07-01

