#     ``zipdetails`` diagnostic on a crafted ZIP.  Neither the minimal
#     perl-base nor anything in the image invokes those paths.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian perl patch; remove each entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed perl-base.
CVE-2026-12087 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-48961 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# gzip 1.13-1 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): two CVEs in the gzip(1)
# command-line package, BOTH UNFIXED in Debian (no FixedVersion via
# ``apt-get upgrade -y``).  Surfaced by the Trivy SARIF scan as GitHub
# code-scanning alerts #378 (CVE-2026-41992, HIGH — global buffer overflow
# in the legacy-LZH decompressor) and #379 (CVE-2026-41991, MEDIUM —
# arbitrary file overwrite via insecure temp-file handling in the ``gzexe``
# wrapper).
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-07-15):
#   - Both flaws live in the gzip(1) BINARY / its ``gzexe`` shell wrapper.
#     CVE-2026-41992 requires the gzip binary to decompress an
#     attacker-controlled legacy-LZH stream; CVE-2026-41991 requires running
#     ``gzexe`` against an attacker-writable directory.
#   - The runtime image never spawns gzip or gzexe: the ONLY external binary
#     the code launches is Stockfish, and there is no first-party reference
#     to gzip/gzexe anywhere in ``llm/`` (grep is clean).  Python-side
#     decompression (httpx Content-Encoding, the stdlib) goes through
#     libz/zlib IN-PROCESS — the DEFLATE path, not the gzip(1) binary's
#     legacy-LZH decoder where the overflow lives.
#   - The service handles HTTP JSON, PGN/FEN text, and Postgres rows; it
#     decompresses no attacker-supplied archives via the command-line tool.
# Accepted risk pending a Debian gzip patch; remove each entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed gzip.
CVE-2026-41992 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-41991 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# libacl1 2.3.2-2+b1 / libattr1 1:2.5.2-3 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13
# Trixie): three symlink / TOCTOU privilege-escalation CVEs in the ACL /
# xattr libraries, ALL UNFIXED in Debian (no FixedVersion via
# ``apt-get upgrade -y``).  Surfaced by the Trivy SARIF scan as GitHub
# code-scanning alerts #380 (CVE-2026-54369, HIGH — symlink-traversal
# privesc via libacl functions), #381 (CVE-2026-54370, MEDIUM — TOCTOU
# symlink traversal via getfacl/setfacl), and #382 (CVE-2026-54371, MEDIUM —
# symlink-traversal privesc via getfattr/setfattr).
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-07-15):
#   - All three require running the ACL/xattr tools (getfacl / setfacl /
#     getfattr / setfattr, or the libacl/libattr functions) against an
#     attacker-controlled path, in a context privileged enough for the
#     symlink swap to escalate.  libacl1/libattr1 are transitive base-image
#     libraries (coreutils links libacl for ACL-aware ls/cp).
#   - The container runs uvicorn as USER appuser (uid 10001, non-root — no
#     privilege to escalate FROM) and never manipulates ACLs or extended
#     attributes: it spawns none of getfacl/setfacl/getfattr/setfattr and
#     has no first-party reference to acl/xattr anywhere in ``llm/`` (grep
#     is clean).  The app touches HTTP JSON, PGN/FEN text, and Postgres
#     rows — never filesystem ACL/xattr metadata on untrusted paths.
# Accepted risk pending Debian acl/attr patches; remove each entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships fixed libacl1 / libattr1.
CVE-2026-54369 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-54370 until:2027-07-01
CVE-2026-54371 until:2027-07-01

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# linux-pam 1.7.0-5 (python:3.13-slim / Debian 13 Trixie): CVE-2026-54411
# (MEDIUM — plaintext password recovery via a timing discrepancy in the
# ``pam_userdb`` module), UNFIXED in Debian (no FixedVersion via
# ``apt-get upgrade -y``).  Surfaced by the Trivy SARIF scan as GitHub
# code-scanning alerts #369-#372 (reported against the libpam0g /
# libpam-modules / libpam-modules-bin / libpam-runtime sub-packages of the
# linux-pam source).
#
# Reachability analysis (2026-07-15):
#   - The flaw is a timing side-channel in ``pam_userdb`` (PAM auth against a
#     Berkeley-DB credential store).  Exploitation requires a PAM-aware
#     service configured to use ``pam_userdb`` AND an attacker able to time
#     its auth attempts.
#   - The application does its OWN auth (JWT + PBKDF2-SHA256, see
#     llm/seca/auth) and never invokes PAM.  No PAM-aware service runs in the
#     container: uvicorn is the only listener; nothing spawns login/su/sshd
#     (same basis as the login(1) CVE-2026-3184 entry above), and the image
#     ships no ``pam_userdb`` configuration.  There is no first-party
#     reference to pam anywhere in ``llm/`` (grep is clean).
# Accepted risk pending a Debian linux-pam patch; remove this entry once
# ``apt-get upgrade -y`` ships a fixed libpam-modules.
CVE-2026-54411 until:2027-07-01
